					<description><![CDATA[<p>Altilium has secured £18.5m in funding to accelerate its vehicle EV battery recycling technology and scale up production of greener battery materials. This agreement is significant for the establishment of</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/altilium-secures-18-5m-to-scale-ev-battery-recycling/" data-wpel-link="internal">Altilium Secures £18.5M to Scale EV Battery Recycling</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://altilium.tech/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Altilium </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has secured £18.5m in </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/elorian-raises-55m-visual-reasoning-ai/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">to accelerate its vehicle EV battery recycling technology and scale up production of greener battery materials. This agreement is significant for the establishment of a circular supply chain for LIBs within the UK.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">There is an ever-increasing demand for the mined raw materials used in EV batteries as their sales grow and consumer preferences shift further towards electric vehicles. This is especially true for nickel, which makes up a large portion of each battery cell and whose extraction is both costly and environmentally damaging. Altilium is one such company attempting to recycle spent EV batteries and recover the raw materials.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This investment of an additional £18.5 million will allow the company to expand its recycling activities and increase its infrastructure, as well as speed up the adoption of its recycling technology.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Scaling Battery Recycling Technology</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Altilium has engineered a relatively advanced battery recycling system which uses a technology aimed at recovering some of the more valuable battery metals contained in used lithium-ion batteries. This is a proprietary system that allows the company to reclaim and reprocess materials that are suitable for use in new EV batteries.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The cathode active materials from waste batteries, as part of this process, are converted into battery-grade cathode active materials to be able to be recycled back into the battery manufacturing supply chain.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_199826" style="width: 829px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-199826" class="size-large wp-image-199826" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Battery-cell-819x1024.jpg" alt="Battery cell" width="819" height="1024" /><p id="caption-attachment-199826" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This establishes a circular-state economy where all the parts of the batteries are recycled and not disposed of, and ultimately stopped from being wasted, reducing the amount of carbon emissions from the process that includes raw materials.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Since the technology asserts that it could open the supply of precious battery minerals from the European resource base, the company suggests that it could be crucial in helping Europe to maintain its current level of supply and achieve its sustainability objectives.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/elorian-raises-55m-visual-reasoning-ai/?amp=1" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Elorian Raises $55M to Scale Visual Reasoning AI</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Supporting the UK’s EV Supply Chain</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The funding will also support the extensive creation of recycling stations for dumping battery waste from electric vehicles and battery factories. </span><span style="font-weight: 400">A core project for Altilium is a proposed large-scale recycling plant in the UK that will have the capacity to recycle thousands of tonnes of battery waste per year. If successful, it could recycle materials from tens of thousands of electric vehicles per year.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Localising the manufacturing of recycled cathode materials helps promote the UK EV battery supply chain and decrease dependence on importing battery minerals. </span><span style="font-weight: 400">This local availability of recycled feedstock could potentially allow battery manufacturers to meet increasing demand while contributing in a broader sense to national net-zero and clean energy ambitions.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Advancing Sustainable Battery Production</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Altilium&#8217;s plans fit in with global initiatives to make electric vehicles more sustainable over their entire life cycle (recycling battery materials not only reduces environmental damage, but it also helps to build a more resilient supply chain for the EV industry)</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company intends to work further with the battery manufacturers, automakers, and recycling partners to enlarge its capacity for recycling.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Altilium will use this fresh funding of 18.5 million pounds to scale up and accelerate the commercialisation of its technology. It will also play a role in creating a more sustainable and circular EV battery ecosystem for the UK and its parts.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/altilium-secures-18-5m-to-scale-ev-battery-recycling/" data-wpel-link="internal">Altilium Secures £18.5M to Scale EV Battery Recycling</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
